 Secret Life of Prince Charming\n|\nMuch later, Alice would wonder what might have happened if she had gone to bed when she was supposed to.\n\n- Django Wexler, The Forbidden Library\n|\nI hear and behold God in every object, yet understand God not in the least, Nor do I understand who there can be more wonderful than myself.\n\n- Walt Whitman, Song of Myself\n|\nIf you do not have control over your mouth, you will not have control over your future.\n\n- Germany\n|\nBoy, those French! They have a different word for everything.\n\n- Steve\n|\nThere is a reason that all things are as they are, and did you see with my eyes and know with my knowledge, you would perhaps better understand.\n\n- Bram\n|\nI am serving the purpose for which I was designed, therefore I am satisfied with my existence.\n\n- Kevin\n|\nGod wants all man's attention, thoughts and focus to be on Him.\n\n- Jaachynma N.E. Agu, The Prince and the Pauper\n|\nThey looked to each other for support, for strength, and at times, motivation, to remember why and for whom they lived.\n\n- Sage Steadman, Upon Destiny's Song\n|\nLove can rebuild the world, they say, so everything's possible when it comes to love.\n\n- Haruki Murakami, Kafka on the Shore\n|\nTo be rich, don’t try to earn money. To grow abundance, never forget to cultivate your mind.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nYou know what I should do?' Hoshino asked excited. 'Of course,' the cat said. 'What'd I tell you? Cats know everything. Not like dogs.\n\n- Haruki Murakami, Kafka on the Shore\n|\nTomorrow always comes with a new hope for a new beginning. After all, it is a new day!\n\n- Debasish\n|\nFreedom means equality. If you don't believe in equality for all, you don't believe in freedom.\n\n- DaShanne\n|\nThere's only one rule you need to remember: laugh at everything and foget everybody else! It sound egotistical, but it's actually the only cure for those suffering from self-pity.\n\n- Anne Frank, The Diary of Anne Frank\n|\nI've heard that the soul often recognizes truth when it hears it, even if the mind does not.\n\n- Richelle Mead, Storm Born\n|\nTo stand on a mountain top, you must first create the mountain.\n\n- Anthony\n|\nEscape is a process, not a pill.\n\n- Beth Kempton, Freedom Seeker: Live More. Worry Less. Do What You Love.\n|\nYes, my scars shape meToday, I have learnt to coverit with fabric made of hope, faith, perseverance, and determination. For this, I am grateful to life\n\n- Vijaya\n|\nThough a new cloth makes you look new, when you see the old cloths, you remember the old life\n\n- Ernest\n|\nWhat if the kid you bullied at school, grew up, and turned out to be the only surgeon who could save your life?\n\n- Lynette\n|\nDon’t look up to people, don’t be someone’s following.Now a days everything you see is just a lie,Instead be the person you want to follow.\n\n- Akash Lakhotia, World Hypnotized: Making of the Fuhrer\n|\nIntelligence won wars, not brute force.\n\n- Rick Riordan, The Staff of Serapis\n|\nWhat I am telling you, before you begin my story, is this -- two things: I crave truth. And I lie.\n\n- Tana French, In the Woods\n|\nHow do you give something away with the knowledge that you will get it back in three days, and then claim it to be the 'Ultimate Sacrifice'?\n\n- Jake\n|\nWealth is a byproduct of positive, wealth-oriented thoughts.\n\n- Debasish\n|\nJourneys end in lovers meeting, Every wise man's son doth know.\n\n- William Shakespeare, Twelfth Night\n|\nMy behavior is nonetheless, deplorable. Unfortunately, I'm quite prone to such bouts of deplorability--take for instance, my fondness for reading books at the dinner table.\n\n- Brandon Sanderson, The Final Empire\n|\nYou don't need to justify your love, you don't need to explain your love, you just need to practice your love. Practice creates the master.\n\n- Miguel Ruiz, The Mastery of Love: A Practical Guide to the Art of Relationship\n|\nAs a poet and as a mathematician, he would reason well; as a mere mathematician, he could not have reasoned at all.\n\n- Edgar Allan Poe, The Purloined Letter\n|\nLet Him easter in us, be a dayspring to the dimness of us, be a crimson-cresseted east.\n\n- Gerard\n|\nMen brave and generous live the best lives, seldom will they sorrow; then there are fools, afraid of everything, who grumble instead of giving.\n\n- Anonymous, The Poetic Edda\n|\nEvery minute you spend in planning saves 10 minutes in execution; this gives you a 1,000 percent Return on Energy!\n\n- Brian\n|\nPeople that love quotes are those short on time, but long on big ideas.\n\n- Bruce\n|\nWithout music, life would be a mistake.\n\n- Friedrich Nietzsche, Twilight of the Idols\n|\nWas there any meaning to life or to war, that two men should sit together and jump within seconds of each other and yet never meet on the ground below?\n\n- David Kenyon Webster, Parachute Infantry: An American Paratrooper's Memoir of D-Day and the Fall of the Third Reich\n|\nIt is not the failure of others to appreciate your abilities that should trouble you, but rather your failure to appreciate theirs.\n\n- Confucius\n|\nArtists, by their free expressions, encourage others to be free. This is the quality that makes works of art enduring.\n\n- Marty\n|\nWriting in a new style never hurt anybody. Upside: if it does, you can write about it!\n\n- Jennifer\n|\nConquering any difficulty always gives one a secret joy, for it means pushing back a boundary line and adding to one's liberty.\n\n- Henri-Frédéric\n|\nDon’t pass on your passions, to settle in the stale normality. Endure. Strive. Ensure.\n\n- Anthony\n|\nHarry, you wonderful boy, you brave, brave man.\n\n- J.K. Rowling, Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows\n|\nI never quite understood the question that says, is the glass half empty or half full? What’s the difference? Eventually it’ll end up empty and in the trash.\n\n- Cyndi Goodgame, Under Cover\n|\n[we see that] science is eminently perfectible, and that each theory has constantly to give way to a fresh one.\n